article.description: Sheri Sam scored 23 points to lead the Sting past the Storm 86-72 in their fourth straight win.
article.headline: Sam lifts streaking Sting past ex-team, slumping Storm
article.linkText: Sam lifts streaking Sting past ex-team, slumping Storm
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Charlotte Sting coach Muggsy Bogues still has bitter feelings over his trade from the Hornets nearly nine years ago, so he knew how Sheri Sam felt.

Sam scored 23 points to lead the Sting past the Seattle Storm 86-72 on Thursday in their fourth straight win.

"It's extra motivation for any player who gets traded from a team and feels it was unjust," Bogues said. "That's the business, but she came out and took care of her business and let them know they're going to miss her."

Sam, who started on Seattle's 2004 WNBA championship team, made 8-of-17 shots and grabbed eight rebounds.

"I have personal relationships with people on that team, and I had dinner on the line," Sam said of her pregame bet with Storm forward Lauren Jackson.

Sue Bird scored 19 points and Betty Lennox added 13 for the Storm (11-12), who committed 18 turnovers in their third straight loss. Jackson had 11 point and five rebounds in her return after missing Tuesday's loss to Sacramento with plantar fasciitis in her left foot.

She wasn't a fan of the trade that sent Sam to Charlotte last season.

"Sheri had the game of her life, she was unstoppable," Jackson aid. "Obviously, she had something to prove, but she should still be playing with us."

Tammy Sutton-Brown added 12 points and Kelly Mazzante scored nine, including six on consecutive 3-pointers in a 10-0 run that put Charlotte ahead 74-59 with 4:31 left. The Sting, who last won four straight in June 2004, committed only nine turnovers and made a season-high nine 3s.

The winning streak has brought up a scenario unthinkable when the Sting were 3-16 at the All-Star break -- the playoffs.

"Mathematically it's not over yet," said Bogues of the Sting, who moved within 4 ½ games of Washington for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. "They believe in each other now and now they're playing basketball, not just running sets. It's a treat to see."

Jackson was forced to carry the load in the paint after Janel Burse injured her left shoulder in a collision with Charlotte's Helen Darling early in the game and did not return.

"Losing JB is a difficult thing for all of us, we don't know how long she'll be out," Storm coach Anne Donovan said. "We're very limited in our post rotation."

The Sting led by as many as 10 points in the second quarter behind Sam's 16 first-half points. The Storm cut the lead to two early in the third quarter, but Mazzante's 3 gave Charlotte a 62-55 lead heading to the fourth.

The Storm played their first game since Tuesday's announcement that they and the NBA's SuperSonics were sold to an ownership group headed by Oklahoma City businessman Clay Bennett. He is considering moving the teams if a new arena deal isn't worked out in Seattle.

"There's no doubt that's been a distraction for everyone on this team," Jackson said.
